9 months in, 9 months out 💪🏼

It’s not a bounce back.
It’s not a comeback.

It’s just working with the new body I’ve got. And with that comes a lot of learning, patience, and acceptance. And I mean a lot. There is still struggle in the “used to’s”.

I know I’m not where I was but I’m working on it and that’s the only thing that matters.

Postpartum or not, it’s important to give yourself grace and have patience with yourself. Goals don’t happen over night. They take time. Weeks. Months. And sometimes years.

Whether you can do it by yourself or you need the help of a trainer, it’s an accomplishment and that’s something to be proud of!

The takeaway? Social media glorifies everything. Some people “bounce back” quick or don’t have to work super hard to reach goals, some people need a little help and some people are comfortable in their skin, whatever season they’re in. All three are beautiful and all three are 100% accepted.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

The holiday season is here and that means it’s time to give yourself a little grace and be kind to that little head of yours. I know the things you say up there…

You hear me say it all the time - life is about balance. You win some, you lose some, and you enjoy the process of both.

Have the extra cookie. Have the glass of wine. Have that scoop of potatoes. All will be okay. I promise!

When you find yourself feeling a little icky, here are a couple of easy things for you —
••> drink a glass of lemon water
••> skip the coffee, grab some green tea
••> go for a walk outside. chilly? the crisp air is good for everything.

When the days are done and the weekend is over, just slip back into your weekly routine and don’t stress about the last 4 days. They’re in the past and it’s time to move forward ✨👍🏼💛
.
.
.
.
.
.

Tell me….

What are your tricks for being productive when you’re home with a little?
-OR-
If you don’t have a little, how do you get things done if you lack motivation?

I absolutely LOVE my time at home with Willow. But trying to get normal, daily tasks done while she’s awake, prove to be more and more challenging as the weeks go by.

THEN when she finally lays down for a nap, I feel so unmotivated. Like I just want to sit and get lost in the sauce while drinking my HOT cup of coffee.

Not to mention - I have a literal job I need to do, too. Not just household chores 😂

Not every day is as productive as yesterday… if you saw my story, you know 😌

Any tips, tricks or advice 👇🏼👇🏼 drop it in the comments. PLEASE.

Sincerely, me.

I don’t know how stay at home moms (or dads) do it all! You’re the real MVP 👏🏼

**don’t take this as complaining or asking for pity. I wouldn’t trade this situation for ANYTHING. I am so blessed to be home with my baby some days

Hi 👋🏼 hello 👋🏼 I am here. Happy Monday! Happy New Year! 🥂✨

After taking about 2 weeks away from posting, I am back with my cheesy Monday motivation post.

I feel like going into the new week, of the new year, maybe we could all use a little inspiration/motivation/sense of balance

It’s simple what I have to say today -

[[Health is important. Total wellness is important. Movement is important. Eating healthy foods are important.]]

BUT if you made a  New Year’s resolution that DOES NOT contain something about your health, ✨THAT IS OKAY✨

If you did not make a resolution, that is okay, too!

Don’t let health and fitness influencers, or even your best friend, trick you into thinking YOU HAVE TO HAVE a health goal.

Because guess what? You can do all of the above, without tying it to a new years goal. That’s intimidating. Just do you.
.
.
.
.
PS - if you DO have a health and fitness goal, that is absolutely fantastic! And I am rooting for you big time! I’m proud of you!
.
.
.
PPS - if you DON’T have a health and fitness goal, I’m rooting for you, too, to have the best year! AND I’m proud of you, too!
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

If you don’t post a picture, the workout didn’t happen, right? Wrong. And that is what leads me into my motivation topic today.

So often, I fall into the mindset that if I can’t get content, then I’m not going to do it. And my personal workouts are jeopardized because of that.

I’m too focused on showing up for YOU that I’m not focused on ME

And I need to show up for myself. Because when it’s all said and done, I have to live with ME not YOU.

So I’m here to tell you that it’s time to focus on you, show up for you, and everyone else can wait.

It’s not always about getting the perfect shot or showing the most growth. Grow personally. And show up in private. It’s not always about letting the world see.

Because you can still be successful. In private!

Happy Monday ☀️👏🏼 I hope you have the best week. Do something for yourself today that you can thank you for later
.
.
.
.
.

Went digging into the summer archives for this one, while I feel a little nostalgic for the past.

Yesterday I met my mom at the gym for a workout, and while I wanted to post this comment to you all yesterday, I decided to wait to see how I felt today after getting through Monday.

The gym was busy. People kept talking. And we did not have a great workout.

While I groaned about the workout not being great and the feeling of not being accomplished in the gym, my mom chimed in -

“Any workout is better than no workout”

And while I continued to dwell on the not so great workout all day, I also continued to tell myself that at least I did something instead of staying home 🤷🏻‍♀️

And today, today I feel great from that workout! No, I’m not sore. But I feel good and now I’m in a better mindset to share this message with you —

Working out is hard.
Accomplishing goals is hard.
Prioritizing movement is hard.

But when you do it, you will feel great about it. Even the worst workouts are better than no workout. Even a five minute walk is better than no walk.

It’s the small things we need to remember that still add up to our greater picture of success.

So next time you feel bad about something POSITIVE you did, remember that at least you did it 🤍
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

A friendly reminder from your friendly pre/postnatal exercise specialist —

In the last week, I have come in contact with multiple ladies who are expecting a baby. SO exciting!

••HOWEVER••

What was all too common in those interactions was the misinformation they had about exercise and pregnancy.

Being told it’s not safe,
they can’t raise their heart rate,
it’s unsafe for baby… blah blah blah.

When the reality is, movement is the best for mama and baby! It’s keeps your body feeling able and strong.

Your joints will feel better
Your labor/delivery will be eased*
You’ll be stronger postpartum
Lowered risk of gestational diabetes*
Stronger core, less risk of c-section
Shortened labor

And so much more! Don’t let old news be your current events for your pregnancy.

If you need a hand along the way, reach out! Here I am 🙋🏻‍♀️🤍
.
.
.
.
.
.

I’ve been meaning to post about this for a while and just haven’t. So here’s the lowdown —>

At the end of January I began a new job. My dream job actually. Since I graduated from college and jumped head first into all things fitness, I’ve dreamed of working for @matrixfitnessusa .

Fast forward through my fitness career, I’ve worked as a full time trainer, I worked in corporate wellness, I went to back to being a full time trainer, then back into corporate wellness, and lastly into business development for corporate wellness.

I thought I made it there. Every single day. I loved every bit of what I was doing. But then, a position opened with @treowellness , the corporate wellness division of Johnson Health Tech (the people who make Matrix)

I would have been a FOOL to not at least try for this position.

I’ve had job alerts for Johnson set since 2016 and FINALLY something opened that I could do.

Now here I am, 6 weeks later, still asking to be pinched because I can’t believe the job I’ve landed.

Now I get to continue helping employers provide their employees with the best wellness solutions while enjoying every benefit for myself as well 💚

I am not one to wish away winter. I enjoy the snow and I welcome the cold.

Overhead Squats
Hover Curtsies

Roll Outs

Mkay so normally my motivation Monday post comes early in the day so we can start off on a good note, but here it is -

Mentally I’m in my pajamas in a hotel room.
Physically I’m sitting at my computer in my office.

It’s Monday. That means the weekly list of to dos has started over and it’s time to get our sh** together.

And let me tell ya - I would much rather sit at my computer and work through my lunch break today than do chores because my head is NOT in it for that.

So instead of taking my hour lunch break, I’m doing 3-5 minute breaks throughout the day that allow me to
> water the plants
> throw in the laundry
> vacuum
> mop
> clean the bathroom
> unload the dishwasher
> and be thankful I get to work from home.

Because in the grand scheme of things, each of these tasks only take a few minutes. So instead of looking at the daunting list of things, I find little spaces I can step away for 3 minutes and cross something off.

I challenge you to find that little bit of motivation within to do, even just one thing, on your list that you
DON’T WANT TO DO

You’ll be so happy it’s done.

Have a great week!

As a prenatal and postpartum exercise specialist, here are my top 8 floor-based core+pelvic floor exercises that I believe you should incorporate into your routine during pregnancy and throughout your postpartum journey.

In the beginning of each video you will see me “set up” the movement by stabilizing my core. This should be done whether you are on your back or on all fours.
**you may need to reset during your reps. You should do so the same way as if you are just beginning the set, even if you only have 2 reps left.
 
You do not need to do all these exercises within the same workout. You can choose 4 today and 4 the next time. However, they are all safe to do at once if you would like to have a designated core workout.

A couple videos say “two variations” - be sure to watch the whole video to see the advanced and modified versions of the movement.
 
It is important to take note of any pressure or coning during your workout. To put it simply – pressure is discomfort and coning is when you core looks like a cone; not flat or engaged. This is NORMAL, just take a moment to reset and reengage. If you’re doing the full/advanced version, step down to modified.

2-3 sets of 12 reps for each
Pelvic Tilts
*deep breath in, exhale tilt your pelvis/flatten your back and hold for :05
Bird Dogs
*set your core, inhale as you lift, exhale as you come to the middle
**modified – omit the middle “crunch”
Bear Drops
*set your core, inhale as you lift, exhale as you lower
**modified – lift one leg, set it down, lift the other.
Single Leg Extension-Raise
*perform a pelvic tilt, extend one leg, lift straight up, reverse the movement, switch legs
**advanced – pelvic tilt, lift your legs to 90*
Glute Bridge
*perform a pelvic tilt, feet should be hip width apart, press through heels to raise hips and squeeze glutes at top. Reset at the bottom
Bear Plank
*set your core, be sure knees are under hips and hold as long as possible
**if coning or pressure occur, lift one knee, hold for :10, then switch and repeat for :60
